    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-07-22T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-07-22T08:00:00-05:00" n="357"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d357">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/948: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-07-22T20:00:00+07:00"
                            >July 22, 1943—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 23—noon.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1260. TF–142 from Adler to Secretary of Treasury only.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Regarding your 911 of July 16. Transmitted your message to Dr. Kung on
                        21st; he indicated that he had already sent a formal request to you.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Regarding your 882, of July 9,<note n="39" xml:id="d357fn39">
                            <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_461">p. 461</ref>.</note>
                        part II, and my TF–141 of July 17.<note n="40" xml:id="d357fn40">Telegram
                            No. 1209, <ref target="#pg_429">p. 429</ref>
                        </note>
                        <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Dr. T. F. Tsiang of Executive Yuan in informal conversation with
                                me on 20th indicated that while a few high government officials
                                regarded sale of gold in China as a panacea, in better informed
                                government circles it was tentatively estimated that about 1 million
                                oz. gold could be sold at roughly CN dollars 8,000 per oz. which
                                would yield enough to cover approximately one fourth of probable
                                deficit for 1943. Dr. Tsiang felt that in absence of definite
                                knowledge as to scale on which gold will be absorbed at worth while
                                prices sale of gold should be begun experimentally and that if
                                experiment is unsuccessful it should be scrapped.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Since Central Government annuled its prohibition of free trading
                                in gold, Shanghai bullion dealers have been coming into Free China
                                to set up business. They constitute majority of the 30 to 40 bullion
                                dealers in Chungking.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>It is suggested that Treasury mark messages of relative urgency “priority”
                        as your messages take an average of not less than 4 days to reach me. Delay
                        in your receipt of my TF–141 due to bad local transmitting conditions.
                        [Adler.]</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
